			p Barebones is a SASS boilerplate to help you build your own front-end framework. It is not a fully-fledged library, but a set of commonly used tools; a grid system, helper classes and a range of mixins, put together in a convenient package to kickstart your next project. Help you structure your custom SASS framework and provide you with all the tools you need to get up and running.

			p Everything in Barebones has been stripped back to include only the bare essentials, so you can spend less time overwriting and more time creating something that looks unique. It is a collection of ideas, which we see as 'best practice' collected from around the Internet, and packed together into a single package. We help to help SASS 'newbies' and other front-end.

			p The best way to use Barebones is to download the source from <a href="https://github.com/sebpowell/barebones">Github</a> and start building!

			a.button.primary.large(href="#{repo}") Download



		article.article


			h2 Why another framework?

			p We created Barebones because we weren't happy with other frameworks. Much has been written on the subject of custom SASS frameworks, and we decided to start doing this ourself. As we did, we learned a lot. We wanted it to be as lightweight as possible, whilst also giving enough firection to help you strcuture your SASS project yourself. Buildingin custom CSS frameowrks is hard. 2 years ago, we made the decusiubs of building or own instead of using a full-fledged framework like Bootstrap. There were various reasons for this, but one of the mains reasons was.  No vendor-prefixing mixins (these can not be handled using your build process) Many librarties provide incredibly basic mixins that don't actually help you much. For example, the Bourbon library provides mixins to simplify certain commands, but it doesn't actually encourage.

			p At the same time, we spent a lot of time reading articles by the likes of Hugo Giraduel, Ben Frain and others that regularly had great ideas for structring projects ina  more maintable way. Things like managing z-index maps etc. If you're starting out, or for people whgi are used to tradtionally CSS, it takes a long time to build up that knowledgebase. By which time, it may be too late to add in best practices you've seen elsewhere. BArebones is here to give you that leg-up, included a set of 'best practices' which we think have genuinely made our lives easier.

