			h2 Installing


			p You can also get the latest release using Bower.


			p You can alos simply dowload the source files, include and get started! The issue with this approach though is that it makes it difficult to upgrade. However if you're happy maintaining your own SASS library (which after all, is part of the philshopy behind this project), then you can do so and then simply update the relevant files when the next realse comes out.

			p Because Barebones doesn't include any components or styling, it won't get in your way. By default, classes are not namespaced, but the project is strcutured to allow you to do this if you wish.

			p You'll need SASS is not supported by web browser, so you'll need to process. There are various ways of doing this, depending on your steup – see the SASS site for more info

			p Barebones is split into two sets of files;
			ul
				li A collection of the core files
				li A global settings file.

			p The settings file acts as a global configuration file – mixins, helpers and the grid system all pull i values from this file. You need this file for Barebones to work – it won't work otherwise.

			p <strong>1. Install the Barebones package</strong>
			pre
				code.language-bash
					| bower install barebones

			p <strong>2. Create a settings file (<a href="../build/settings.html">see here</a> for more info)</strong>

			p 3. Create a new SASS file, import the settings file first followed by _base.sass.

			p
				li - libs/barebones/_base.scss
				li - assets/scss/styles.scss
				li - assets/scss/_settings.scss

			p Your styles.scss file should look like this:

			pre
				code.language-scss
					| @import _settings.scss // Always import the settings file first
					| @import _base.scss // Import Barebones
					| // Your stuff can come here.



			pre
				code.language-scss
					| @import "_settings.scss"
					| @import "bower_components/dist/_base"

